
2. Verify Access Rights
Ensure you have read/write permissions to the repository.
For private repositories:
Confirm that your GitHub account is a collaborator or that your access token/SSH key has the right permissions.
3. Authenticate Properly
a) For HTTPS
If using HTTPS, GitHub requires a personal access token instead of a password:

Generate a token:
Go to GitHub Settings > Developer Settings > Personal Access Tokens.
Generate a token with the required scopes (repo for full access to repositories).
Use the token instead of your password during authentication.
b) For SSH
If using SSH, ensure:

Your public SSH key is added to your GitHub account:
Generate a key if you don’t have one:
bash
Copy code
ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096 -C "your.email@example.com"
Add the key to your GitHub account by copying it:
bash
Copy code
cat ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub
Go to GitHub: Settings > SSH and GPG Keys and add the key.
Test your SSH connection:
bash
Copy code
ssh -T git@github.com
You should see a success message like Hi <username>! You've successfully authenticated.
4. Verify the Repository Exists
Ensure the repository exists under the specified account or organization.
Double-check for typos in the repository name or owner name.
To check a repository’s existence:

Go to the repository URL in your browser: https://github.com/username/repository.
5. Debug Further
a) Check Branch Name
Ensure you’re working on the correct branch. Modern repositories default to main instead of master.

b) Verbose Mode
Use verbose mode to gather more details about the error:

bash
Copy code
GIT_TRACE=1 GIT_CURL_VERBOSE=1 git pull
